ğŸ§  First, simple definition (no jargon)

An adapter is a translator between Rails and the outside world.

Rails doesnâ€™t know how to send an email.
It only knows what an email is.

So Rails says:

â€œHereâ€™s an email. Someone please deliver it.â€

The adapter is that someone.

ğŸ“¦ In Action Mailer terms
config.action_mailer.delivery_method = :smtp


Here:

:smtp = adapter

It tells Rails which delivery mechanism to use

Other adapters:

:smtp
:sendmail
:test
:file


Each adapter knows how to send the email in its own way.

ğŸ”Œ What exactly is SMTP then?
SMTP = Simple Mail Transfer Protocol

Think of it as:

HTTP for emails

Just like:

HTTP sends web requests

SMTP sends emails

SMTP defines:

How to connect to a mail server

How to authenticate

How to send the message

ğŸ“¨ SMTP Adapter Flow (under the hood)
Rails (Action Mailer)
   â†“
Mail gem
   â†“
SMTP adapter
   â†“
SMTP server (Gmail / SES / Outlook)
   â†“
Recipient inbox


Rails does not implement SMTP itself.

The Mail gemâ€™s SMTP adapter does.

ğŸ§  Mental analogy (easy to remember)
Sending a letter ğŸ“¬

Rails = writes the letter

Adapter = chooses delivery service

SMTP = India Post / FedEx

Recipient = mailbox

If tomorrow you change:

delivery_method = :sendgrid


You changed courier, not the letter.

âš™ï¸ SMTP Adapter responsibilities

The SMTP adapter:

Opens TCP connection

Authenticates (username/password)

Sends email data

Handles retries / failures

Closes connection

Rails never deals with this directly.

ğŸ” Why adapters exist (VERY important)

Because Rails wants this:

UserMailer.welcome(user).deliver_later


To work without caring:

Gmail

Outlook

SES

Local dev

Test environment

Adapters make this pluggable.

ğŸ§ª Example: test adapter
config.action_mailer.delivery_method = :test


Here:

No SMTP

No network

Emails stored in memory

ActionMailer::Base.deliveries.last


Same API, different adapter.

ğŸ†š SMTP vs API adapters (SendGrid, SES)
Adapter	How it sends
SMTP	Protocol-based
SendGrid API	HTTP REST
SES API	HTTP REST

But Rails code stays the same:

deliver_later


ğŸ’ Thatâ€™s the power of adapters.

